    "instruction": "Please load metric.csv and trace.csv from the current working directory and return a compact summary for each file. For metric.csv: (1) total row count, (2) list of unique cmdb_id values, (3) top 20 kpi_name values with their counts, (4) minimum and maximum timestamp values. For trace.csv: (1) total row count, (2) list of unique cmdb_id values, (3) top 20 trace_name values with their counts, (4) minimum and maximum timestamp values. Keep outputs concise (no more than the requested aggregates and at most 20 rows for lists). Do not convert timestamps to datetime." 
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor output: metric.csv contains 90,678 rows across 56 cmdb_id values (includes db_001..db_013 and docker_001..docker_008 among others) with many KPI names (top KPIs listed). trace.csv contains 6,240 rows across 10 cmdb_id values (docker_001..docker_008 and os_021, os_022) with many trace_name entries. These summaries confirm available components and KPIs and that we must compute global thresholds on the full series before filtering to the incident window (2020-04-11 01:30–02:00). Next we need global thresholds per component-KPI to detect anomalies. No filtering by incident time should be done when computing these thresholds.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full metric.csv (no time filtering), aggregate by cmdb_id and kpi_name and compute these aggregates for each component-KPI series: count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, P50 (median), P90, and P95 of the 'value' column. Return the top 20 component-KPI rows sorted by P95 descending. Include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, p50, p90, p95. Keep the output limited to these aggregated rows (max 20). Do not convert timestamps to datetime." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global P95 thresholds for all component-KPI series and then scanned the incident window (2020-04-11 01:30–02:00 UTC+8). The top anomalous series (by breaches_count and severity_ratio) are dominated by node-level KPIs (os_*), with the single largest deviation being os_007 / Processor_load_1_min (severity_ratio ≈ 160). os_007 also shows Processor_load_5_min breaches with the same earliest breach timestamp (1586541000). Multiple node KPIs (os_019, os_008, os_020, etc.) also show breaches but with notably smaller severity ratios. According to the root-cause rules, the most significant deviation across levels points to the node-level fault as the likely root cause candidate. We now need to confirm whether os_007 shows a true fault (a consecutive anomalous sub-series) within the incident window and determine the exact first anomalous timestamp and supporting KPIs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For os_007, analyze only these two KPIs: Processor_load_1_min and Processor_load_5_min. Do the following in code: (1) Using the full metric.csv (no time filtering), compute the global P95 of 'value' for each of the two (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series. (2) Filter metric.csv to the incident window April 11, 2020 01:30–02:00 (UTC+8). (3) For each of the two KPIs within that window, return: all rows where value > global_p95 (columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value), the global_p95, count_of_breaches, earliest_breach_timestamp, latest_breach_timestamp, max_value_in_window, and severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_p95. (4) Determine whether the breach timestamps form a consecutive run (i.e., sorted breach timestamps differ by exactly 60 seconds between adjacent points). Limit the output to the requested aggregates and at most the breach rows (max 20). Do not convert timestamps to datetime in this step." }

{
    "analysis": "We confirmed os_007 has consecutive, multi-KPI breaches in the incident window: Processor_load_1_min and Processor_load_5_min both exceeded their global P95 at three consecutive timestamps (1586540760, 1586540820, 1586540880). Processor_load_1_min shows an extremely large severity_ratio (~160), far above other series. However, other node-level components (os_019, os_008, os_020, etc.) also show breaches in the same window. According to the diagnosis rules, node-level faults do not propagate; the root cause level should be chosen by the fault with the most significant deviation from thresholds. To confirm os_007 is the predominant node-level root cause (not one of several independent node faults), we need an aggregate view of how many distinct KPIs per node breached their P95 in the window and the maximum severity per node. This will let us decide whether os_007 is the single predominant faulty node and provide the exact first breach timestamp to report as the root cause occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the previously computed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name), produce a node-level summary for all cmdb_id that begin with 'os_'. For each node compute: (1) faulty_kpi_count = number of distinct kpi_name that have at least one value > global_p95 within the incident window (2020-04-11 01:30–02:00 UTC+8), (2) earliest_breach_timestamp = the minimum timestamp across all breaches for that node, (3) max_severity_ratio = the maximum (per-kpi max_value_in_window / global_p95) across all that node's KPIs, and (4) total_breaches = total number of breach datapoints across all KPIs in the window. Return rows limited to nodes with faulty_kpi_count>0, sorted by max_severity_ratio descending, then total_breaches descending. Include columns: cmdb_id, faulty_kpi_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, total_breaches, max_severity_ratio. Limit output to top 20 rows."}

{
    "analysis": "The node-level summary shows widespread anomalies across many os_* nodes starting at or near the incident-window start (timestamps around 1586539800). Many nodes produce infinite severity ratios because some KPIs had global P95 == 0 while observed values in the window were non-zero — indicating sudden non-zero spikes from a zero baseline. This pattern across many nodes at the same time suggests a systemic issue rather than a single-node CPU fault. To determine whether this was a network-related incident (network loss/delay) vs. systemic load, we need to inspect network-related KPIs (Incoming_network_traffic, Outgoing_network_traffic, Recv_total, Send_total, ICMP_ping, etc.) across the os_ nodes during the incident window and see whether they show drops (low values) or spikes. Finding simultaneous drops in traffic or ping failures would point to network loss/delay; simultaneous spikes in disk or CPU across many nodes could point to load or scheduling issues. Therefore the next atomic step is to extract network-related KPI anomalies per os_* node within the incident window using the already computed global P95 thresholds, focusing on breach counts, earliest breach timestamp, and severity to help decide the root cause reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the global P95 thresholds (computed on full series), filter metric rows to the incident window April 11, 2020 01:30–02:00 (UTC+8). For cmdb_id values that start with 'os_', select KPI rows where kpi_name contains any of these substrings (case-sensitive): 'network', 'Recv', 'Send', 'ICMP_ping', 'Ping'. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: breaches_count (value > global_p95), earliest_breach_timestamp (min timestamp of breaches), max_value_in_window, p95 (global), and severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / p95 (handle p95==0 as separate flag). Keep only rows with breaches_count>0. Return up to 20 rows sorted by earliest_breach_timestamp ascending then severity_ratio descending. Include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, breaches_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95, severity_ratio, p95_zero_flag (True if p95==0)."
}

